		<td><b>Re: tom7's &quot;Reverse emulating the NES to give it SUPER POWER</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Why? To define terms, which per Layne's Law of Debate is necessary before productive debate can continue.<br /><br />When discussing the limits of the NES platform, one must first define what is considered an &quot;NES game&quot;. Is an NES game still an NES game if it runs the majority of a game on a coprocessor in the cartridge? No one would sincerely argue that <em>Star Fox</em> and <em>Super Mario RPG</em> aren't Super NES games, but I imagine they draw the line somewhere before a Wide Boy or Super Game Boy or an Xbox game played through what amounts to a TV tuner cartridge.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


